2022 was one heck of a year🫶🏼 It was a mix between my most difficult year full of hardships and challenges, but also my year of great growth and love. 

I learned all about professional rejection. I learned what it feels like to be truly loved and cared for by people who are not your blood. I allowed myself to truly fall in love for the first time in a long time. I made fitness a priority. I didn’t beat myself up on the times I had fitness setbacks. I took up a new hobby and started hockey. I went out of the country for the first time. I gained a nephew. I set strong boundaries in specific relationships. I learned more about myself. And y’all, my hair got pretty dang long lol. 

Here’s to 2022…now we are ready for ya 2023✨🥂

the parts of yoga Instagram doesn’t always show… the moments we lose our balance 🙃

the key to maintaining your center of stabilization in any pose, especially balance poses, is to find your drishti. 

your drishti, or focused gaze, is where you place your intention or concentration. Finding your drishti will allow you to keep your mind engaged and focused as you find your breath and pose. 🧘🏼‍♀️

the yoga pose is not the goal. flexibility, stability, and headstands are not the goal. 

the goal is to turn your attention inwards. to notice your breath and be aware of your physical body. to tune into your thoughts and where your mind wanders. to notice your emotions and pull back the layers guarding your heart. the goal of yoga is to be aware and appreciate all that you are in this life.

Well hot damn. I climbed the #ManitouIncline and made it to the top😅🗻

I’ve done my fair share of hiking while living in WNC, but let me tell you that was BY FAR the hardest hike I’ve ever done. My calves are dead. 

I almost quit three times on the hike but I knew if I got off the incline I’d regret it. I was afraid of falling, the altitude was making it hard to breathe, and I was in a mix of freezing (39°) and sweating haha. But hey, making it to the top was all worth it!! ….then had a 3-mile hike back down…

This hike is equivalent to climbing the Empire State Building, the Eiffel Tower twice and hiking  the🗽 6 times — definitely felt like it too😅

✨2 YEARS✨ I’ve been feeling a little discouraged the past few days thinking about where I want to be physically…and while I’m so close, it’s been a struggle for me to get there. 

I’m mostly wanting to get stronger (upper body mostly) a little leaner, and build my cardiovascular fitness level to where running a half marathon won’t be the death of me. 

But I found these pictures last night from March 2021 and wow. I haven’t been giving myself enough credit for how far I’ve come. In 2020 I weighed 212 pounds. I weigh 152 currently. That’s 60 pounds. That’s a ton of determination and effort. That’s a ton of sweat and tears and motivation to get where I am today. 

Even though it doesn’t feel like the biggest win for not being quite where I’m hoping to be, I need to celebrate the milestone of where I am now. 

So don’t sell yourself short. It’s a marathon, not a sprint. Celebrate every mile and stop for water.

All cats go to heaven right?🐱🤍 

We had to say goodbye to our little Tigger yesterday. ”Bubba,” “Bub,” “Tig,” “Tig-a-RO,” “lil chicken,” had a full life of 12 years. While it doesn’t feel as if that was near long enough, the Goforth family was blessed with such a special cat. 

We found the little nugget when he was about 6 weeks old in 2011. He was so cute I begged dad to keep him. Tigger was one of those “that f’n cat” situations that dads do, but once I left for college Bub became Papa Bear’s best buddy. They kept each other company so the house was never empty. Stella grew attached to him and he was one of her first pet experiences. 

Bubba had definitely spent his 9 lives…from being shot twice, dealing with a few infections, he stayed happy and healthy even in his old age. Always catching birds and squirrels. 

Tigger was the most sweetest, loving, needy, biscuit-making, meow screeching, goodest of boys and he is already missed. 💔

one of my favorite things about Hinduism is understanding yoga mudras — your gesture or “mark” using your fingers and hand to symbolize the flow of energy within.

5 healthy practices I’ve learned you need to establish as an adult:

🌊 Continue to learn. Reading books, taking classes, research, videos, etc. keeps your mind sharp and brain active. 

🌊 Try new things and find a hobby. Starting hockey this year really pushed me out of my shell and motivated me to be tough and more athletic. Embracing my inner Disney adult also allowed me to connect to my inner child. 

🌊 Learn self awareness. I preach this in yoga, but know how to be self aware mentally, physically and emotionally. This is key to a more happy and healthy life. 

🌊 Make time to socialize in person. Social media is cool and all, but you have to learn how to make friends as an adult. I’m sorry, but drinking and partying shouldn’t be your only “social” experience. 

🌊 Know your boundaries and establish them. Have boundaries with yourself…think about goals you set and keep yourself accountable. Set boundaries with work, friends, family, and romantic partners. This allows your cup to be filled and for you to help fill others.

Raise your hand if you have TMJ🙋🏼‍♀️

I have struggled with severe TMJ since late high school and sadly as an adult it’s only gotten worse. 🥲 I tend to clench my jaw when I workout, play hockey, and especially when I sleep. I’ll wake up with insane migraines and that lovely jaw crackling. 

Since I’m not ready to consider jaw surgery or something more invasive just yet, Botox has been the way to go. 

dr.harry.acevedo fixed me up with 25 units of Jeuveau in each masseter to provide relief in those muscles. 

If you are suffering from TMJ, I strongly suggest you check out @endothetics because you’ll be in great hands!

ahhh I love some egg bites 🍳😋 and these make the best simple yet satisfying breakfasts. Plus, you can always change up the ingredients for variation. 

🍳12Tbs of egg whites 
🍳1/2 cup of cottage cheese
🍳1/2 cup reduced fat shredded cheese
🍳3.5 servings of Canadian bacon 
🍳salt + pepper to taste 

I blend the egg whites and cheese, spray the pan, add Canadian bacon, then pour the mixture on top! Bake at 350°F for about 15-20 minutes. Pop in the microwave to reheat. 🙌🏼

pov: you start playing hockey in your twenties 🏒

It’s officially been a year since I started playing hockey for the first time. Let me tell you, this hobby hasn’t been easy. There’s been blood, sweat and tears involved…plus, quite a few bruises lol. 

Deciding to take on a new sport is never easy. Learning a new sport as an adult…even more of a challenge…and trust me when I say it will humble you. 

I’m thankful to have taken on this amazing sport — especially as we try to normalize more and more women/girls lacing up skates and clipping on helmets. 

This year I’ll be working on goalie (and still skating out) so stay tuned for so much more progress and work. 🏒⛸️🥅
